===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|雔|又|t1=two birds|t2=hand|ls=ic}} – Represents two birds ({{zh-l|*隹}}) in someone's right hand ({{zh-l|*又}}).

===Etymology===
Several etymologies have been posited:
* From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*dzum ~ tsum||pair}}, whence {{cog|kac|zum||to be in pairs}}, {{cog|my|စုံ||pair}}, but this comparison may be problematic given the mismatch in the final nasal (STEDT, {{zh-ref|Hill, 2019}}).
* Related to {{cog|bo|ཟུང||pair; couple}}, {{cog|mro|tr=choŋ|t=pair}} ({{zh-ref|Coblin, 1986}}; {{zh-ref|Löffler, 1966}}; {{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}), but this would require assuming the {{cog|sit-pro|-}} word to be {{m|sit-pro||*C-zuŋ}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). {{zh-ref|Jacques (2015b)}} rules out the possibility of comparing with the {{cog|bo|-}} word because {{cog|bo|-}} ''z-'' usually comes from ''*dz-''.
* Doublet of {{och-l|孿|twin}} ({{zh-ref|Baxter, 1992}}), but this has been related to {{cog|kac|marun||to have twins}} (from {{m|kac|run||to be in pairs}}), which would point to yet another {{cog|sit-pro|-}} root {{m|sit-pro||*run}} ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}).

